x4freetext: -NEUTRON ELASTIC SCATTERING IN THE ENERGY REGION
1.5 TO 4.0 MEV FOR RADIOGENIC LEAD AND BISMUTH.
STUDSVIK 6 MV VAN DE GRAAFF ACCELERATOR
EQUIPPED WITH A PULSING AND KLYSTRON BUNCHING
SYSTEM. DELIVERS BURSTS OF PROTONS AT A
REPETITION RATE OF 1 MHZ WITH A PULSE WIDTH AT
HALF MAXIMUM OF ABOUT 1.2 NS AND AVERAGE BEAM
CURRENT OF 3 MICROAMPS.
TARGET CELL OF LENGTH 1.5 CM FILLED WITH
TRITIUM GAS TO A PRESSURE OF 1.0 ATM. THE
MOLYBDENUM ENTRANCE WINDOW OF THE CELL HAD A
THICKNESS OF 4 MG/CM2. THE TOTAL ENERGY SPREAD
WAS ESTIMATED TO BE LESS THAN +/- 30 KEV.
THE INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES WERE DETERMINED
BY USING A TOF DIFFERENCE BETWEEN NEUTRONS
AND GAMMA-RAYS FROM THE TARGET OVER A KNOWN
FLIGHT PATH.
.THE SAMPLES WERE AS HOLLOW CYLINDERS OF 3.0 CM
HEIGHT AND OUTER DIAMETER OF 1.8 CM AND INNER
DIAMETER OF 0.95 CM.
THE BI SAMPLE WAS OF THE NATURALLY OCCURING
ELEMENT BI-209 WITH A PURITY OF AT LEAST 99.5
PERCENT.
THE LEAD SAMPLE CONSISTED OF RADIOGENIC LEAD WITH
A COMPOSITION OF 88.2 PERCENT  PB-206
8.8 PERCENT  PB-207
3.0 PERCENT  PB-208.
DURING THE EXPERIMENTS THE SAMPLES WERE POSITIONED
AT A DISTANCE OF 14.5 CM IN FRONT OF THE TARGET.
TWO IDENTICAL 12.7 CM BY 5.1 CM THICK
LIQUID SCINTILLATORS MOUNTED ON FAST
PHOTOMULTIPLIER TUBES WERE USED TO MEASURE
THE ANGULAR DISTRIBUTIONS OF ELASTICALLY
SCATTERED NEUTRONS. THE DETECTORS WERE SEPARATED
BY AN ANGLE OF 5 DEGREES IN THE AZIMUTHAL PLANE
AND WERE POSITIONED AT A DISTANCE OF 300 CM FROM
THE SCATTERING SAMPLE IN A HEAVY SHIELDING.
THE TOTAL TIME RESOLUTION WAS 1 NS FWHM, THE
ACTUAL ANGLES WERE DETERMINED BY MEANS OF A
DIGITIZER WITH AN ANGULAR RESOLUTION OF LESS
THAN 0.1 DEGREES.
THE NEUTRON FLUX WAS DETERMINED USING A
TOF NEUTRON MONITOR CONSISTING OF A 5 CM BY 5 CM
FAST PLASTIC SCINTILLATOR COUPLED TO A FAST
PHOTOMULTIPLIER TUBE.
.THE CROSS SECTIONS WERE DETERMINED RELATIVE TO
THE N-P SCATTERING CROSS SECTION.
OPTICAL MODEL PARAMETERS.
LEGENDRE COEFFICIENTS DETERMINED.
DATA TAKEN FROM MAIN REFERENCE.
PN
A.L. LEGENDRE POLYNOMIAL COEFFICIENTS
INCLUDED.
.THE BACKGROUND SPECTRUM FROM THE SAMPLE-IN SPECTRUM
WAS SUBTRACTED AFTER THE NEUTRON FLUX NORMALIZATION.
THE DIFFERENT DETECTOR EFFICIENCIES WERE CORRECTED
FOR. THE ANGULAR DISTRIBUTIONS WERE CORRECTED FOR
ANISOTROPY OF THE NEUTRONS FROM THE H-3(P,N) RECTION,
FINITE ANGULAR GEOMETRY, FLUX ATTENUATION IN THE
SCATTERING SAMPLES AND MULTIPLE SCATTERING. A
MONTE CARLO PROGRAM WAS USED TO TREAT THE LATTER
THREE EFFECTS.
THE ATTENUATION AND MULTIPLE SCATTERING IN THE
POLYTHENE SAMPLES USED FOR CALIBRATION WERE
CORRECTED FOR BY APPLYING THE PARALLEL BEAM FLUX
TABLES GIVEN BY CRANBERG AND LEVIN MULTIPLIED BY
1.01 TO CORRECT FOR THE DIVERGENCE OF THE NEUTRON
BEAM.
.OVERALL UNCERTAINTIES IN THE INDIVIDUAL CROSS
SECTIONS AND IN THE ANGLE INTEGRATED TOTAL
ELASTIC CROSS SECTIONS ARE BETWEEN 4.1 AND 5.4
PERCENT AND BELOW 4.0 PERCENT RESPECTIVELY.
